(lp3
VAs a culture, we tell ourselves lots of stories
p4
aVabout the future,
p5
aVand where we might move forward from this point.
p6
aVSome of those stories are that
p7
aVsomebody is just going to sort everything out for us.
p8
aVOther stories are that everything is on the verge of unraveling.
p9
aa(lp10
VBut I want to tell you a different story here today.
p11
aVLike all stories, it has a beginning.
p12
aVMy work, for a long time, has been involved in education,
p13
aVin teaching people practical skills
p14
aVfor sustainability,
p15
aVteaching people how to take responsibility
p16
aVfor growing some of their own food,
p17
aVhow to build buildings using local materials,
p18
aVhow to generate their own energy, and so on.
p19
aa(lp20
VI lived in Ireland, built the first straw-bale houses in Ireland,
p21
aVand some cob buildings and all this kind of thing.
p22
aVBut all my work for many years was focused
p23
aVaround the idea that sustainability
p24
aVmeans basically looking at
p25
aVthe globalized economic growth model,
p26
aVand moderating what comes in at one end,
p27
aVand moderating the outputs at the other end.
p28
aVAnd then I came into contact with a way of looking at things
p29
aVwhich actually changed that profoundly.
p30
aa(lp31
VAnd in order to introduce you to that,
p32
aVI've got something here that I'm going to unveil,
p33
aVwhich is one of the great marvels of the modern age.
p34
aVAnd it's something so astounding and so astonishing
p35
aVthat I think maybe as I remove this cloth
p36
aVa suitable gasp of amazement might be appropriate.
p37
aVIf you could help me with that it would be fantastic.
p38
aV(Laughter)
p39
aVThis is a liter of oil.
p40
aa(lp41
VThis bottle of oil,
p42
aVdistilled over a hundred million years of geological time,
p43
aVancient sunlight,
p44
aVcontains the energy equivalent of about five weeks
p45
aVhard human manual labor \u2014
p46
aVequivalent to about 35 strong people
p47
aVcoming round and working for you.
p48
aVWe can turn it into a dazzling array of materials,
p49
aVmedicine, modern clothing,
p50
aVlaptops, a whole range of different things.
p51
aVIt gives us an energy return that's unimaginable, historically.
p52
aVWe've based the design of our settlements,
p53
aVour business models, our transport plans,
p54
aVeven the idea of economic growth, some would argue,
p55
aVon the assumption that we will have this in perpetuity.
p56
aa(lp57
VYet, when we take a step back,
p58
aVand look over the span of history,
p59
aVat what we might call the petroleum interval,
p60
aVit's a short period in history
p61
aVwhere we've discovered this extraordinary material,
p62
aVand then based a whole way of life around it.
p63
aVBut as we straddle the top of this energy mountain, at this stage,
p64
aVwe move from a time where our economic success,
p65
aVour sense of individual prowess and well-being
p66
aVis directly linked to how much of this we consume,
p67
aVto a time when actually our degree of oil dependency
p68
aVis our degree of vulnerability.
p69
aa(lp70
VAnd it's increasingly clear that we
p71
aVaren't going to be able to rely on the fact that
p72
aVwe're going to have this at our disposal forever.
p73
aVFor every four barrels of oil that we consume,
p74
aVwe only discover one.
p75
aVAnd that gap continues to widen.
p76
aVThere is also the fact that the amount of energy
p77
aVthat we get back from the oil that we discover is falling.
p78
aVIn the 1930s we got 100 units of energy back
p79
aVfor every one that we put in to extract it.
p80
aVCompletely unprecedented, historically.
p81
aVAlready that's fallen to about 11.
p82
aVAnd that's why, now,
p83
aVthe new breakthroughs, the new frontiers
p84
aVin terms of oil extraction are scrambling about in Alberta,
p85
aVor at the bottom of the oceans.
p86
aa(lp87
VThere are 98 oil-producing nations in the world.
p88
aVBut of those, 65 have already passed their peak.
p89
aVThe moment when the world on average passes this peak,
p90
aVpeople wonder when that's going to happen.
p91
aVAnd there is an emerging case
p92
aVthat maybe that was what happened last July
p93
aVwhen the oil prices were so high.
p94
aa(lp95
VBut are we to assume that the same brilliance
p96
aVand creativity and adaptability
p97
aVthat got us up to the top of that energy mountain in the first place
p98
aVis somehow mysteriously going to evaporate
p99
aVwhen we have to design a creative way back down the other side?
p100
aVNo. But the thinking that we have to come up with
p101
aVhas to be based on a realistic assessment
p102
aVof where we are.
p103
aa(lp104
VThere is also the issue of climate change,
p105
aVis the other thing that underpins this transition approach.
p106
aVBut the thing that I notice, as I talk to climate scientists,
p107
aVis the increasingly terrified look they have in their eyes,
p108
aVas the data that's coming in,
p109
aVwhich is far ahead of what the IPCC are talking about.
p110
aVSo the IPCC said
p111
aVthat we might see significant breakup
p112
aVof the arctic ice in 2100, in their worst case scenario.
p113
aVActually, if current trends continue,
p114
aVit could all be gone in five or 10 years' time.
p115
aVIf just three percent of the carbon locked up in the arctic permafrost
p116
aVis released as the world warms,
p117
aVit would offset all the savings that we need to make,
p118
aVin carbon, over the next 40 years to avoid runaway climate change.
p119
aVWe have no choice other than deep and urgent decarbonization.
p120
aa(lp121
VBut I'm always very interested to think about
p122
aVwhat might the stories be
p123
aVthat the generations further down the slope from us
p124
aVare going to tell about us.
p125
aV"The generation that lived at the top of the mountain,
p126
aVthat partied so hard, and so abused its inheritance."
p127
aVAnd one of the ways I like to do that
p128
aVis to look back at the stories people used to tell
p129
aVbefore we had cheap oil, before we had fossil fuels,
p130
aVand people relied on their own muscle, animal muscle energy,
p131
aVor a little bit of wind, little bit of water energy.
p132
aa(lp133
VWe had stories like "The Seven-League Boots":
p134
aVthe giant who had these boots, where, once you put them on,
p135
aVwith every stride you could cover seven leagues, or 21 miles,
p136
aVa kind of travel completely unimaginable
p137
aVto people without that kind of energy at their disposal.
p138
aa(lp139
VStories like The Magic Porridge Pot,
p140
aVwhere you had a pot where if you knew the magic words,
p141
aVthis pot would just make as much food as you liked,
p142
aVwithout you having to do any work,
p143
aVprovided you could remember the other magic word to stop it making porridge.
p144
aVOtherwise you'd flood your entire town with warm porridge.
p145
aa(lp146
VThere is the story of "The Elves and the Shoemaker."
p147
aVThe people who make shoes go to sleep, wake up in the morning,
p148
aVand all the shoes are magically made for them.
p149
aVIt's something that was unimaginable to people then.
p150
aa(lp151
VNow we have the seven-league boots
p152
aVin the form of Ryanair and Easyjet.
p153
aVWe have the magic porridge pot
p154
aVin the form of Walmart and Tesco.
p155
aVAnd we have the elves in the form of China.
p156
aVBut we don't appreciate what an astonishing
p157
aVthing that has been.
p158
aa(lp159
VAnd what are the stories that we tell ourselves now,
p160
aVas we look forward about where we're going to go.
p161
aVAnd I would argue that there are four. There is the idea of business as usual,
p162
aVthat the future will be like the present, just more of it.
p163
aVBut as we've seen over the last year, I think that's an idea
p164
aVthat is increasingly coming into question.
p165
aVAnd in terms of climate change,
p166
aVis something that is not actually feasible.
p167
aa(lp168
VThere is the idea of hitting the wall,
p169
aVthat actually somehow everything is so fragile
p170
aVthat it might just all unravel and collapse.
p171
aVThis is a popular story in some places.
p172
aVThe third story is the idea that technology can solve everything,
p173
aVthat technology can somehow get us through this completely.
p174
aa(lp175
VAnd it's an idea that I think is very prevalent at these TED Talks,
p176
aVthe idea that we can invent our way out of a profound
p177
aVeconomic and energy crisis,
p178
aVthat a move to a knowledge economy
p179
aVcan somehow neatly sidestep those energy constraints,
p180
aVthe idea that we'll discover some fabulous new source of energy
p181
aVthat will mean we can sweep all concerns
p182
aVabout energy security to one side,
p183
aVthe idea that we can step off neatly
p184
aVonto a completely renewable world.
p185
aa(lp186
VBut the world isn't Second Life.
p187
aVWe can't create new land and new energy systems at the click of a mouse.
p188
aVAnd as we sit, exchanging free ideas with each other,
p189
aVthere are still people mining coal
p190
aVin order to power the servers, extracting the minerals
p191
aVto make all of those things.
p192
aVThe breakfast that we eat as we sit down
p193
aVto check our email in the morning
p194
aVis still transported at great distances,
p195
aVusually at the expense of the local, more resilient
p196
aVfood systems that would have supplied that in the past,
p197
aVwhich we've so effectively devalued and dismantled.
p198
aa(lp199
VWe can be astonishingly inventive and creative.
p200
aVBut we also live in a world with very real constraints and demands.
p201
aVEnergy and technology are not the same thing.
p202
aVWhat I'm involved with is the transition response.
p203
aVAnd this is really about looking the challenges
p204
aVof peak oil and climate change square in the face,
p205
aVand responding with a creativity and an adaptability
p206
aVand an imagination that we really need.
p207
aVIt's something which has spread incredibly fast.
p208
aVAnd it is something which has several characteristics.
p209
aa(lp210
VIt's viral. It seems to spread under the radar very, very quickly.
p211
aVIt's open source. It's something which everybody who's involved with it
p212
aVdevelops and passes on as they work with it.
p213
aVIt's self-organizing. There is no great central organization
p214
aVthat pushes this; people just pick up an idea
p215
aVand they run with it, and they implement it where they are.
p216
aVIt's solutions-focused. It's very much looking at what people can do
p217
aVwhere they are, to respond to this.
p218
aVIt's sensitive to place and to scale.
p219
aa(lp220
VTransitional is completely different.
p221
aVTransition groups in Chile, transition groups in the U.S., transition groups here,
p222
aVwhat they're doing looks very different in every place that you go to.
p223
aVIt learns very much from its mistakes.
p224
aVAnd it feels historic. It tries to create a sense
p225
aVthat this is a historic opportunity
p226
aVto do something really extraordinary.
p227
aVAnd it's a process which is really joyful.
p228
aVPeople have a huge amount of fun doing this,
p229
aVreconnecting with other people as they do it.
p230
aVOne of the things that underpins it is this idea of resilience.
p231
aa(lp232
VAnd I think, in many ways, the idea of resilience
p233
aVis a more useful concept than the idea of sustainability.
p234
aVThe idea of resilience comes from the study of ecology.
p235
aVAnd it's really about how systems,
p236
aVsettlements, withstand shock from the outside.
p237
aVWhen they encounter shock from the outside
p238
aVthat they don't just unravel and fall to pieces.
p239
aVAnd I think it's a more useful concept than sustainability, as I said.
p240
aa(lp241
VWhen our supermarkets have only two or three days' worth of food in them
p242
aVat any one time, often sustainability tends to focus on
p243
aVthe energy efficiency of the freezers
p244
aVand on the packaging that the lettuces are wrapped up in.
p245
aVLooking through the lens of resilience,
p246
aVwe really question how we've let ourselves get into a situation
p247
aVthat's so vulnerable.
p248
aVResilience runs much deeper:
p249
aVit's about building modularity into what we do,
p250
aVbuilding surge breakers into how we organize the basic things that support us.
p251
aa(lp252
VThis is a photograph of the Bristol and District
p253
aVMarket Gardeners Association, in 1897.
p254
aVThis is at a time when the city of Bristol,
p255
aVwhich is quite close to here,
p256
aVwas surrounded by commercial market gardens,
p257
aVwhich provided a significant amount of the food
p258
aVthat was consumed in the town, and created a lot of employment for people, as well.
p259
aVThere was a degree of resilience, if you like, at that time,
p260
aVwhich we can now only look back on with envy.
