aa(lp262
VSo how does this transition idea work?
p263
aVSo basically, you have a group of people who are excited by the idea.
p264
aVThey pick up some of the tools that we've developed.
p265
aVThey start to run an awareness-raising program
p266
aVlooking at how this might actually work in the town.
p267
aVThey show films, they give talks, and so on.
p268
aVIt's a process which is playful and creative
p269
aVand informative.
p270
aVThen they start to form working groups, looking at different aspects of this,
p271
aVand then from that, there emerge a whole lot of projects
p272
aVwhich then the transition project itself
p273
aVstarts to support and enable.
p274
aa(lp275
VSo it started out with some work I was involved in in Ireland,
p276
aVwhere I was teaching, and has since spread.
p277
aVThere are now over 200 formal transition projects.
p278
aVAnd there are thousands of others who are at what we call the mulling stage.
p279
aVThey are mulling whether they're going to take it further.
p280
aVAnd actually a lot of them are doing huge amounts of stuff.
p281
aVBut what do they actually do? You know, it's a kind of nice idea,
p282
aVbut what do they actually do on the ground?
p283
aa(lp284
VWell, I think it's really important to make the point that actually
p285
aVyou know, this isn't something which is going to do everything on its own.
p286
aVWe need international legislation from Copenhagen and so on.
p287
aVWe need national responses. We need local government responses.
p288
aVBut all of those things are going to be much easier
p289
aVif we have communities that are vibrant and coming up with ideas
p290
aVand leading from the front, making unelectable policies electable,
p291
aVover the next 5 to 10 years.
p292
aa(lp293
VSome of the things that emerge from it are local food projects,
p294
aVlike community-supported agriculture schemes,
p295
aVurban food production, creating local food directories, and so on.
p296
aVA lot of places now are starting to set up their own energy companies,
p297
aVcommunity-owned energy companies,
p298
aVwhere the community can invest money into itself,
p299
aVto start putting in place
p300
aVthe kind of renewable energy infrastructure that we need.
p301
aVA lot of places are working with their local schools.
p302
aVNewent in the Forest of Dean: big polytunnel they built for the school;
p303
aVthe kids are learning how to grow food.
p304
aVPromoting recycling, things like garden-share,
p305
aVthat matches up people who don't have a garden
p306
aVwho would like to grow food, with people who have gardens they aren't using anymore.
p307
aVPlanting productive trees throughout urban spaces.
p308
aVAnd also starting to play around with the idea of
p309
aValternative currencies.
p310
aa(lp311
VThis is Lewes in Sussex,
p312
aVwho have recently launched the Lewes Pound,
p313
aVa currency that you can only spend within the town,
p314
aVas a way of starting to cycle money within the local economy.
p315
aVYou take it anywhere else, it's not worth anything.
p316
aVBut actually within the town you start to create these economic
p317
aVcycles much more effectively.
p318
aa(lp319
VAnother thing that they do is what we call an energy descent plan,
p320
aVwhich is basically to develop a plan B for the town.
p321
aVMost of our local authorities, when they sit down to plan
p322
aVfor the next five, 10, 15, 20 years of a community,
p323
aVstill start by assuming that there will be more energy,
p324
aVmore cars, more housing,
p325
aVmore jobs, more growth, and so on.
p326
aVWhat does it look like if that's not the case? And how can we embrace that
p327
aVand actually come up with something that was actually more likely
p328
aVto sustain everybody?
p329
aVAs a friend of mine says, "Life is a series of things you're not quite ready for."
p330
aVAnd that's certainly been my experience with transition.
p331
aVFrom three years ago, it just being an idea,
p332
aVthis has become something that has virally swept around the world.
p333
aVWe're getting a lot of interest from government. Ed Miliband,
p334
aVthe energy minister of this country, was invited to come to our recent conference
p335
aVas a keynote listener.
p336
aVWhich he did \u2014
p337
aV(Laughter)
p338
aV(Applause) \u2014
p339
aVand has since become a great advocate of the whole idea.
